commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-92 - Initialize Unwrapping key

Description:
Failed to unwrap the key using the Unwrapping key after restarting
the device.

Root cause:
After reboot, the Unwrapping key reference is NULL.

Solution:
If the Unwrapping key reference is NULL, get/generate the key.

Change-Id: Ib68cb79cc7e6312a4bf7c4a34a168a46588b09d0
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-92 - Initialize Unwrapping key

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-78 - Update for compiling with libtommath 1.2.0-3

Update for compiling with libtommath 1.2.0-3 on Ubuntu 20.04.
- replace deprecated mp_unsigned_bin_size with mp_ubin_size
- replace deprecated mp_to_unsigned_bin with mp_to_ubin
- replace deprecated mp_read_unsigned_bin with mp_from_ubin
Add wrappers to keep compatibility with libtommath 1.1.x.

Change-Id: I9f24719d4195bceee3363289f322814d45c2cf1e
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-78 - Update for compiling with libtommath 1.2.0-3

comments.message: The code looks good to me but without a dependency manager this will break people who haven't installed the updated libtommath library.  I suppose this can be done later.  Also, I don't see the Klocwork record can we fix this before submitting.
Comment removed by: Paul Chan; Reason: reword

Hi Alex, compilation of iks was broken before this PR. It is not the PR that breaks other people.
I believe you are using old Ubuntu 18.04/16.04 with old libtommath (1.0.x) , as the future will be using Ubuntu 20.04 (comes with 1.2.x) or newer, while backward compatibility is kept at iotKeyStore/pa/linux/pa_crypto.c , this PR enables other teams to work with the current/latest environment .

Again, we need support on Ubuntu 20.04 and we need this PR.
We should fix complilation of iks as a priority, so the proper automated checks can be done on these changes.
Paul, it depends on how someone installed libtommath...  Anyways, I am agreeing to this change but the CI must contain a Klocwork scan before this change can be submitted.

IOTKEYSTORE-91 - Public keys are not stored into keystore path

Root cause:
The temporary path used by IKS to stores the keys is not
initialized, resulting in failure to save keys properly.

Solution:
Create the temporary path on IKS PA initialization.

Signed-off-by: Doreen Tang <dtang@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-91 - Public keys are not stored into keystore path

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-4517 - Altair API sometimes takes a long time.

Description:
Altair ISE2 API sometimes takes a long time. One of the problems is
calling ISE2 API fails. sometimes get error -1 from the ISE2 API and
calling again will succeed.

Improvement:
Altair recommends using MSE_PS_WRAPPER to wrap all ISE2 APIs.
Failure still occurs, but the failure rate is reduced.

Change-Id: Id71f25841e8397f160ec0d94fbdc66a1a3c79490
commits.subject: ALT1250-4517 - Altair API sometimes takes a long time.

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-4428 - Change hl78 IoT keystore architecture design for ISE2

Description:
This commit contains all IoT thinclient request functionality as shown below.
And ECC encryption and decryption are supported in this commit

Function Implement:
ALT1250-4140 - [ISE2] Implement key management API
ALT1250-4321 - [ISE2] Implement Random Number Generator API
ALT1250-4318 - [ISE2] Implement Session Management API
ALT1250-4138 - [ISE2] Implement AES GCM interface
ALT1250-4142 - [RK3.2+] Implement HMAC interface to iSE2
ALT1250-4320 - [RK3.2+] Implement TLS interface to iSE2

Change-Id: I289037ae222de8bc65573ab76dec798d61c469cd
commits.subject: ALT1250-4428 - Change hl78 IoT keystore architecture design for ISE2

The PS_CipherComputeTag function only returns certain tag sizes.  Those restrictions should be documented here.
I'm not sure what you mean. PS_CipherComputeTag can only compute tags bigger than 4 bytes. Do you mean this?

According to the iSE2 documentation "GCM is defined for the tag sizes 128, 120, 112, 104, or 96, 64 and 32".
While here we allow anything size tags so if the caller asks for a tag of 110 bytes then they'll get 6 bytes of garbage in the their buffer without knowing it.
I did some tests for it and I found that the tag size cannot be smaller than 4 bytes. It can work from 4 bytes to 16 bytes. I've created an Altair ticket to ask this question.

According to Altair's ticket answer (https://altairsemi.atlassian.net/servicedesk/customer/portal/1159/SWI1-891), the tag size is bigger or equal to 4 bytes and smaller or equal to 16 bytes (128 bits)
Don't need this.

If I don't, it executes the PS_CipherAddAAD function when aesGcm_Decrypt is called.
The following is the Altair's document. They require the PS_CipherAddAAD need to be called.

PS_CipherAddAAD()
Description
The function passes additional data to an active AEAD operation. Additional data is authenticated, but not encrypted. This function CAN be called multiple times to pass successive fragments of the additional data. This function MUST not be called after passing data to encrypt or decrypt.
The caller MAY pass AAD as NULL (with aad_len set to zero) to indicate there is no AAD to process, this is required to proceed to encrypt/decrypt processing, even if there is no AAD processing to be done.

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1250-4140 - [ISE2] Define ISE2 config

Description:
1. Enable ISE2 config if the ISE2 is enabled in HL78
2. Disable the following defination if the ISE2 enable
   IKS_AES_CBC_ENABLED
   IKS_AES_MILENAGE_ENABLED
   IKS_AES_CMAC_ENABLED
   IKS_RSA_ENABLED
   IKS_AES_MILENAGE_OP_ENABLED

Root cause:
   ISE2 doesn't support AES_CBC, AES_MILENAGE, AES_CMA, and RSA.

Solution:
   Disable config.

Change-Id: I31e6a5512c006d34db4829710c62a81d8fbf8549
Signed-off-by: Doreen Tang <dtang@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: ALT1250-4140 - [ISE2] Define ISE2 config

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-80 - Add simple memory measurement on linux

Add simple memory measurement on linux to caculate the used heap and
process memory used by test iks binary.
- used heap - by measurement in linux's pa_crypto.c
- consumed process memory - by 'time -v' using run_test.sh
- test summary - create run_test.sh to grep info into summary.log

e.g. EXT_LIBS=\"tomcrypt\" BUILD_ARCH=i386 ./run_test.sh

Change-Id: Ib301b87f94bf0441c3bf159651138ba0da6ec86a
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-80 - Add simple memory measurement on linux

comments.message: There are lots of memory profiling tools in Linux already (ps, pmap, valgrind, etc.) so I don't think this change is necessary.
With those tools, how do you calculate the consumption of mem_alloc and average consumption key_t/digest_t ?

In mem.c there is already a malloc_count and the malloc sizes are already logged.  Memory info could also be found looking at /proc/PID/maps.  The Massif for valgrind is pretty good.  Or you could just add some log statements in the places you need.  Log code is good because they get compiled depending on the log level.

The changes were moved to the core. If MEM_PROFILING is enabled, it will collect the heap usage total & max in IKS instead of malloc_count.

Enabling DEBUG_PRINT will show too many traces that masked off the key results, and currently malloc_count is only referenced in DEBUG_PRINT. These are for debug purpose, not profiling run-time.

Memory profiling is usually useful at run time as well, we may keep the code built in if we need to. However, it may be inapplicable to IKS. We may also build another performance profiling to measure the time used in processing time and RPC and so on - ideally it is necessary as I heard QTEE access was quite slow.

As the feature is necessary while it is only enabled by default on Linux, I hope you can see the value of having it.
I'm not convinced that this change is necessary or has enough value to justify the code changes.  I'd like to abandon this change.  Brad do you have an opinion?
Changes are excessive and I also don't see much value of it.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-81 - Update Key test case to use 100 keys

16 extra keys (EXTRA_KEYS_TEST) are currently tested in IKS. This
updates Key test case to use 100 keys in the test, and show the
average heap consumption per key in test log.

Change-Id: Id631178a9a076e1ac458871cc3b3acc4a19727fb
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-81 - Update Key test case to use 100 keys

comments.message: If the intention is just to increase the number of test keys then the changes can be limited to the test code.  Besides the added APIs iks_GetNumOfKeys and iks_GetNumOfDigests are misleading as these only return the number of keys that have been accessed not the total number of keys created/available.

I'd really prefer not to add this to the external API as it is not used anywhere else except for this testing.  Also, it is misleading because this only returns keys that have been loaded into memory.
Agree.

I'd really prefer not to add this to the external API as it is not used anywhere else except for this testing.  Also, it is misleading because this only returns keys that have been loaded into memory.
Agree.
Ack
Maybe we can set the number of test keys to be an optional test argument to accommodate different platforms.

Where should we put this definition ?
It seems config.h is local in core/src only, maybe we put this to iks_config.h instead.
Maybe we can add an optional command line argument.
I think we should either abandon this change or add the number of keys to test as an optional command line parameter.  In which case changes are contained only in the test code.

Agree with Alex's points. The test code and core code are independent and they might not have access 
 to same header files since they are built in different spaces. Might not want to add max test key defines in core code.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-83 - Support singly linked list

Support single linked list in place of double linked list to remove
previous pointer in each link object. Without previous pointer :
- the speed on finding previous pointer is negligible (on key's
  addition/removal) because the total number of keys are typically
  small, say under 200
- key look up is not affected, the list is tranversed one by one to
  look up a key
This saves 4 bytes for each key.

Change-Id: I5a408b1427e7b7fc12bab3dcb6ddc3f3c179a128
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-83 - Support singly linked list

comments.message: I think it would be good to push the list data structure to the PA and make optimizations (memory/runtime tradeoffs) there.  A generic list API can be exposed to the core code while the list can be implemented in the PA with whatever is most appropriate (linked-list, hash map, etc).

I think the proper fix is to push this down into the PA to allow different platforms to optimize for memory/execution time by using data structures that are most suited for them, eg. linked lists, hash maps, etc.

Let's create a pa/common and move it there then.
As you gave a -1 rather 0, did I miss something else ?
Because of the way the ticket is worded, I think should either close this ticket and create another one or reword the ticket.  Yes, I think creating pa/common is the right way.

I moved doublyLinkedList.c to be pa_dll.c under pa/qtee, and pa_sll.c under pa/hl78; while linux will reuse to both of them by symlinks.

See if this is what you expect.

I'm not sure if saving one pointer per key is worth the trouble but to do this right I would do:

 - Add a core/pa/pa_collections.h file that defines an API for a collection of objects.
 - Update the core code to call pa_collections.h functions instead of doublyLinkedList.h functions.
 - Move the doublyLinkedList.h/c to the Linux PA and use it to implement collections.c.
 - Other PAs such as qtee can reference the Linux PA's collections.c.
 - The HL78 PA can create singlyLinkedList.h/c and use it to implement collections.c.

But again, unless 4 bytes per key is critical I would not go through the trouble so for now I suggest this change be abandoned.  Brad, what do you think?

The changes are excessive and savings are minimum. Comparing to the key structure (60 bytes for symmetric key and 100 bytes or more for asymmetric key) the 4 byte saving can be ignored, that means to support 15 keys or an extra key in a constrained device with the cost of readability and maintainability.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-77 - Reduce storage of type and size in key/digest struct

Use storage type of smaller size for type & size in key/digest struct:
- key's keyType : from iks_KeyType_t (8) to uint16_t (4)
- key's keySize : from size_t (4) to uint16_t (4)
- digest's digestSize : from size_t (4) to uint8_t (1)

Change-Id: I7becf841e4fbff2da7f1a9e6cd1721f0dfff5c75
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-77 - Reduce storage of type and size in key/digest struct

comments.message: I don't have a problem with reducing the sizes but I think we need to reflect it in the API then.  Also, I think the digestSize should be a minimum of 2 bytes.
Since the size savings is minimal I'd rather not make this change and allow the compiler to choose the right sizes for the platform.

In fact, it is saving 2+ bytes for each of them including saving from the padding.
And I want this be implemented on HL78.

To simplify this, I suggest
1. type - change to use a bool instead
2. keyType - set IKS_KEY_TYPE_MAX in iks_KeyType_t to 0xFFFF as the range of it value is under 65535
3. keySize - use specific local type to save the keySize, and add compile time assertion to ensure they are within the theoretical limit.
In the HL78 what is the size of size_t, ItemType_t, iks_KeyType_t?

Do you really think that saving a few bytes per key in memory is really worth it?  How many keys do you think there are going to be in a real HL78 device?  I question the need to do this when there are likely large savings to be had elsewhere.

For generic API set like IKS that can be applicable to any products, I think we can measure its memory/flash usage, and progressively turn it into a thin layer to the HW security backend.

I think the maintenance effort is low on using a correct storage size to buffer a context/variable. And the 8 bytes can be saved without affecting the software flow/design. For 128 keys/digests, 12 bytes for each can save ~1.5k bytes but this amount is valid to be saved without significant effort.
I'd prefer to abandon this change.  The memory savings is minimal.  Typical IoT devices will not have very many keys and the memory usage will be dominated by the key values themselves.

Yes the savings are minimum for example:
- key's keyType : from iks_KeyType_t (4) to uint16_t (2)
The storage structure change will also break existing devices.
Uploaded patch set 1.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-84 - Use malloc for key id and digest id

Instead of using fixed size memory for the id, use dynamic size
to save up to 45 bytes for each key.

Change-Id: Ifcbdd0897a3f00feb0aee62a7ef61c8bc98c4421
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-84 - Use malloc for key id and digest id

comments.message: In production systems the client and IKS are not directly linked together and do not share memory.  Instead API calls are made across an IPC mechanism so this change would not work.  The available testClient cheats and links directly with the IKS code only because we never got around to building an IPC link for the Linux PA.
Using dynamic memory for the IDs is good but I don't think this code is ready for submission.
I don't think we need to make this a configuration item.
Okay.
Ack
To reduce changes I think we can leave this is in Item_t.

It won't work if we put it in Item_t because the idea is to allocate memory for id at the end of the structure.
So the addresses of id for Key_t and Digest_t are different.
I'd like to keep these types of changes to a minimum and focus on the stated ticket.  If there is a need for these changes please raise another ticket.
Okay.

        PROJECT-1234 - [AR758x][Keyword] My summary
        PROJ1-1234 PROJ2-4567 - My summary with multiple tickets

 - Your first line should separate the ticket declaration(s) from the summary with a dash.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-85 - Use malloc for update-key's id

Use malloc for update-key's id on demand. This saves the run-time
memory because not all the keys need to be updated. This saves about
46 bytes static memory for each key.
This change also renames KS_PLATFORM_HL78 as KS_PLATFORM_AISE to be
applied to core/src/config.h .

Change-Id: Ia7f3e83b73881db072f75ce1540444c2153b38a0
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-85 - Use malloc for update-key's id

comments.message: Using heap memory for the update key ID is good and will reduce memory usage in general so I don't think we need to make this a config item.  Please update and ensure Klocwork scans this change.
I don't think we need to make this a config item.
Okay.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-79 - Support building with i386 and tomcrypt from source

Support building with i386 and tomcrypt from source:
- i386 - to align with our 32bits embedded architecture for comparative
  behaviour such as pointer size and memory measurement
- tomcrypt - libtomcrypt-dev is not provided in latest debian repo, we
  compile it in source using tomcrypt's tag 1.18.2 with explcit EXT_LIBS
  and default LIB_TOMCRYPT_VER = 1.18.2
e.g. EXT_LIBS=\"tomcrypt\" BUILD_ARCH=i386 make test

Change-Id: I2372ed684e8cbd14df4f516bb2033cdc80d9a03c
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-79 - Support building with i386 and tomcrypt from source

comments.message: Building the external lib from source is a great idea but I'd rather not do it this way.  I'd rather have the libtomcrypt as a submodule and build from there which will make this build more self-contained and less dependent on the environment.

Do you mean that you want to download libtomcrypt even we don't build that ?
Or you want to always build with libtomcrypt ?

You provided -1 rather than 0 for this minor change, is this all that you expect ? Anything else ?

I think we should make libtomcrypt and libtommath a git submodule and build them from source.  Then everyone will always be using the same version of the library and the libraries can be updated along with the source.  I think we can keep the ticket but either abandon this change or create submodules for it.  In any case this does not seem to be a pressing issue as it only effects the Linux PA.
Ack
Uploaded patch set 1.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-76 - Reuse memory from base for key and digest storage

Reuse memory from base for key/digest storage:
- add field 'uint16_t reserved' to base structure
- rename field members from keyType, kySize and dgestSize to mKeyType,
  mKeySize and mDigestSize
- reuse memory from base.reserved

Change-Id: Ia276ae3cafeb1f7314bc1a01cd086ed6f7a7223a
Signed-off-by: Paul Chan <pchan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-76 - Reuse memory from base for key and digest storage

comments.message: It seems the only memory savings is due to the alignment.  I'm not sure what the reserved field is used for.

Compilers use biggest/default system alignment for data structure, for sake of performance by using fast instructions.
For storage structure in memory, we may align it to smaller unit, or even make them packed.

e.g. for 32bit machine, compiler prefers to use 32bit instruction set rather than 8bit or 16bit instructions - for performance. Hence data structure ends at 4-bytes boundary.
To define the data structure to take 22 bytes rather than 24 bytes, we use 2 bytes alignment here.

The reserved field is reused for mKeyType and mDigestSize.
Uploaded patch set 1.

comments.message:
do we need to say the max label size is 252?
If two different labels are provided but the first 252 characters are the same, then it would provide the same key
Added a note on the size limitation in API header.
Maybe we should move this function into an iks_keyDerivation.h file.
Done

Maybe instead of truncating the label, this function should fail so that misuses are more obvious.  Also, the max label size should be in the iks_config.h or maybe the IKS_MAX_PACKET_SIZE could be used instead.
Done
just to double-check, this is ok to be 4096+4 in size?
yes, since it is malloc'ed the size can be as big as 4KB + 4. If the platform is constrained, it can redefine IKS_MAX_LABEL_SIZE to a smaller size.

comments.message: Hi Alex, mostly clarification comments. Also, why did testClient.c need to be edited - line terminations?

The testClient.c file was the only one that had crlf rather just lf.  Maybe it was opened/saved in a Windows editor previously.  I think this is the same reason why sometimes I see the permission bits are changed which I always try fix too.

It might not ready to be enabled on other PAs. QTEE PA currently share this config, would it make sense to add its own config.h for QTEE PA? I can add one quickly so that this review will trigger the CI failures.
Yes, please.

Added: https://gerrit.legato/c/IoTkeystore/+/75787

Another comment is that can you add more info on HSS: what is it stands for and what standards this implementation is based on in commit message?
OK.
On second thought I've added more details to the ticket and kept the commit message succint.

General question: would FARM be able to handle it and run the 'git sumbmodule' commands?

Another comment might be in future we need to rehost the submodule in our git server instead of github if there are too many traffics.
I know Legato uses git submodules quite a bit so the farm should be able to handle it.  If we see build failures here due to the submodule I'll talk to the farm team about how to fix it.

Should probably update any hardcoded library names in comments to include hash-sigs, although you could argue you don't need to reference the library here and that the #include in the code itself is self-documenting.
I will add the comment.
could this test data be placed in a separate test data / fixtures file? I know this doesn't really exist in IKS at present, but testClient.c is becoming a bit lengthy.
Yes, thought about doing that but was concerned that other platforms might not be prepared to push inputs to these tests.  Decided that would be better handled as a testing improvement ticket.
It will be interesting to see if these changes will work on HL78. It has not yet been included in the CI build, so we don't really know.

CI failure and looks like I had similar failure when trying to pull in submodule:
git submodule update
16:19:26 Cloning into '/home/jenkins/workspace/IoT-Keystore-Build/IoTkeystore/iotKeyStore/pa/linux/hash-sigs'...
16:19:28 fatal: remote error: upload-pack: not our ref 497e4c16786e4a16935141ab8ac8db18dd1852ea
Klocwork doesn't seem to be running either.  I'll talk to the farm team.

@Alex it seems like 497e4c16786e4a16935141ab8ac8db18dd1852ea is not a valid commit id. See comment on FARM ticket https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/FARM-5508?focusedCommentId=7952674&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-7952674
It was verified that git submodule update works well if replacing it with current head of master branch commit id "7fe77790b1d16eccd70e052507b5d3f89fb0a942".
Thanks Hong, I found the problem.  Will push a patch soon.

comments.message: A couple of quick comments. In general looks OK to me and fit into the existing PA framework but I haven't looked into too details yet.
The file name is misleading. If needed, I think we can add these function prototypes into core/pa/*.h.

Name can be changed, let me know what would be appropriate one.
I find that it is much preferable to have a simple include file that doesn't contain any of the  IoT keystore specific defines so that it can be included from outside the IKS code. For example, this one is included by the system initialization code.
There are now updates to the linux PA version of this file that should be incorporated here.  Probably don't need the changes for fuzzing but some other minor fixes should be incorporated.
Change ported, fuzzing skipped.
HL78 rather than Linux.
Done

I understand that the HL78 currently has no "secure" place to store the root key but it should still generate the key from the RNG rather than use this hard-coded key so that the keys are unique for each module.

I opened a separate Jira issue for this - ALT1250-4124. There is also a new function in this file that will produce the RPK once the new scheme is implemented - pa_rpk_get(). Until then the current implementation is a Proof Of Concept.
Use of the CRYPT_OK return code for mp_ functions was a mistake.  Let's change them to MP_OKAY instead of this cast here and in the Linux PA.
Done
Seems like this should halt the process.
Done
So, is this meant to be a PoC?
I'll remove this comment once we have the mechanism to store unique RPK. Until then this is a PoC.
Delete commented out code.
Done
Delete commented out code.
Done
This function is already in testClient.c?
Good catch, this was old test code that escaped!
I'd rather keep PA specific stuff out of the core code.  Could you use the PRODUCT_CONFIG_H instead.
Moved definition into product_config_hl78.h
Remove this comment because it is not true.
Done
Does this descriptor actually pull from the HL78's central RNG?
Yes
We would actually do this via the iSE2's API.
Done

Done
Disable for HL78?
Done
Could just comment this line out instead of the #if, #endif wrap.
Done
Comment out.
Done
Copy-paste error?
Done
Looks good to me. The changes are mostly for HL78 and shouldn't affect other platforms.
Edi, can you add some info on the der.c changes in commit message? Looks like that is the only core change and might deserve more background info.

Edi, please address remaining comment on patch 8.
Patch 8 already has +1 and please provide details on new patch 9 so that it is easier to review.

Brad, regarding der.c - it is a change that Alex created when I was encountering some issues on HL78 due to the endianness. The original intent was for Alex to create a separate check in request only for that core issue, but I included it here as part of my code. 
Patch 9 contains changes that were triggered due to changes in the patch 6 of the crypto libraries changes (https://gerrit.legato/c/external/altair/1250/map/+/73686). There was a request to reorganize registration of the random number generator and move the changes into the pa_crypto.c. Eventually the changes were placed into a new file - pa_rng.c .
Hi all, how do I turn on notifications for comments generated in this repo? I get them for all other repos but not for this one.
One minor comment.
Are these just left over debug messages?  If so they should be removed.
Yes, embarrassing leftover, removed them all!

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-58 - Update provisioning format

- Remove version from PublicKey structure because it is not needed.
- Add key fingerprinting.
- Clarify ECPoint and PKCS #1 encoding.
- Update RawCmd format and change order of encryption and signing to sign-then-encrypt.
- Change der API to support optional encodings and context specific tags.
- Delete challenge when authenticated command is verified to keep challenge fresh.
- Remove NULL-terminators in DER encoded strings for language independence.

Change-Id: I15cc496971aa780baad3111d804c53c5b245a264
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-58 - Update provisioning format

comments.message: is the extra 'wrapping' word needed?
That is the doxygen tag for the section.
might want to add comment above that 36 is the max encoding overhead
Done
question: do the key ID IA5 string encoding include the '\0'? I thought IA5 string encoding length = strlen and don't need to include the '\0' at the end of the value.
IA5 strings do not require the NULL terminator but I've included it in our spec just to make processing easier.  I can remove it if you feel strongly about it.

That is fine if we make it clear in the spec. Current spec doesn't specify the NULL terminator so in the related device token encoding I didn't include the extra EOS for "suaWrapKey" and "iksWrapKey" key ID. We could add in the spec that requires all key name/ID must need a EOS.
OK, for the sake of language independence let's drop the NULL-terminator here.  I will update the code and spec to match.
Here and other places, can be DER_CONTEXT_SPECIFIC | 0x00 to reflect that the tag is 0.
Done
same question if the EOS char need to be included and checked in the encoding.

general: don't know if we want to write the asn.1 and der lib from scratch which could be error prone. Maybe in future we can consider to port or borrow something from an off the shelf lib if more DER functions need to be added.
Yes, we can revisit this in the future.  I was planning to do some memory optimizations when decoding but that may not be worth it.
This line can be moved to line 422? So the index can be updated between line 422 and here if need to.
Done
somebody could misinterpret this as += 1. Might just change the variable name to 'len'.
Done
why not do the der_EncodeSeq as before? Wouldn't this cause storage compatibility (one with SEQ encoding and one without)?
The extra encoding is unnecessary.  No compatibility issues since we are still in pre-release.

Wouldn't EncodeSeq be better? The der_EncodeList result don't include the top level length so no idea how long is the structure.
Is this just to save a couple of bytes or for other reasons? Most other places uses der_EncodeSeq.

Yes, this is just to save between 2 and 4 bytes per key.  The sequence encoding doesn't seem necessary as this is only encoded/decoded here.  I noticed that I didn't change the digest storage to match which I'll do.
The NULL pointer check need to be moved up at line 2265 before UnwrappingKeyRef fingerprint is calculated?
Done
might need to update the spec: the spec "PublicKeyValue format including all encodings", need to be updated that ASN.1 encoding might not be needed (for ECPoint)
Yes, will do.
data?
Done
This is only for iksWrappingKey, suaWrappingKey is out of the scope, right?
Yes, but I guess it could be used for both.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-24 - Get version string from repo

Auto update the version string header file as
part of build process. The version string will be
read from repo through git command and will be used
by iks_getVersionStr API.

Change-Id: I07bf7f249198d704fd6ecac2463f2d5adacf1d64
Signed-off-by: Brad Du <bdu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-24 - Get version string from repo

comments.message:
One of the reasons the original version numbers were integers was to make comparisons easier.  The would only be converted to text for display.  Keeping everything as a string is fine as long as the conventions for the updates are spelled out so that chronological comparisons are possible.

Also, I thought we agreed that we would set the version in the code and have the build/release system pull the version from here.

The build system will update this version string automatically. For example in the review build:
07:02:33 testClient.c 2623 | Testing IOT Key Store Version: IOTKEYSTORE_00.02.00.00-18-g80d8a03
Should this function (tz_app_init) fail if there is an error?

This function doesn't have a return value and that is defined by QTEE framework - I guess it can crash to stop keystore TZ app from running but that is not what we want.
Adding an else case to log the error instead.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-49 - [QTEE PA] Fix update key related test cases

Including the following changes:
- Add as_Init() as a test case. Didn't add it as part of init
  function since as_Init function will take a long time to
  generate RSA keys. Also we might not want to call this test
  init function to generate test keys which is not suitable for
  production devices.
- Fix a bug in core key management code that a local variable
  is being used after free. This is causing authenticated
  provisioning function failure.
- Fix a bug in QTEE storage PA to test if a file can be created.
  This is causing authenticated update of digest failure if
  the digest is already in storage.

Change-Id: Ia63bdd99d04d7c5925b03f4f793800e94e1a454b
Signed-off-by: Brad Du <bdu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-49 - [QTEE PA] Fix update key related test cases

comments.message: function

That is a 3KB large variable and These large local variables are causing issues - people have to increase stack size for their processes.
I think for longer term we'd like to move all these large variables to malloc. This change is a small step towards that.
Yes, we met the same issue in RC76 QMI library because of the stack size, which finally we allocate the QMI message buffer from heap to avoid stack overflow.

Here we need call iks_DeleteKey() to delete the test Key if we don't follow the test pairs dependency like in GcmPacketTest ("!HasPersistentData" for encryption and "HasPersistentData" for decryption ).

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-14 - Add support for key provisioning using ECC

Including the following changes:
- Add ECIES packet encryption and decryption functions.
- Add key provisioing using ECC. RSA or ECC key type is added
  as one of the input parameter for the key provisioning API.
- Increased max parameters supported in RPC call from 12 to 16.
- Add ECC support in local key wrapping and new test case for
  ECIES packet encryption/decryption.
- Other general code cleanup and improvements especially in
  area of malloc and memory measurement.

Change-Id: Ib0c351903047167a01779d57f583f7cea26a2b49
Signed-off-by: Brad Du <bdu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-14 - Add support for key provisioning using ECC

comments.message: There's a bunch of code here that is a repeat of the code in aesGcm.c which has always made me uncomfortable.  Maybe we can take this opportunity to improve this.
This will make the provisioning key available to the client for use which was something I specifically wanted to avoid.

My intention was for each IKS instance there would only be a single supported provisioning key type and size that would be chosen at build time.  Do you really think we need to allow the caller to choose the provisioning key type and size?

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-47 - Fix memheap crashes on RC76 iks client

The thread stack is too small to run iks client and the
stack overflow also causes heap corruption since thread
and its stack is dymanically allocated. Fix this by moving
the test client to its own task with larger task stack size.

Some other minor formatting change to fix compiler warnings.

Signed-off-by: Brad Du <bdu@sierrawireless.com>

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-32 - Free items in memory to reduce memory usage

When too many key/digest items are cached in memory, free item
values if they can be reloaded from persistent storage when
needed.

Change-Id: If41bae44ce53d2a59a8ad682b1849f2bb3c8d8c7
Signed-off-by: Brad Du <bdu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-32 - Free items in memory to reduce memory usage

comments.message: I'm not sure if we should make this public.
moved to keyManagement.c
I think that we should just not free the key if it is being used in a session otherwise the session state will be lost unexpectedly.
Added the check that if a key is used in a session then it will not be freed.
remove blank line
Done
persistent?
Done

This will actually delete the key from memory invalidating the client's key reference unexpectedly.  I was thinking that we would just free the value and then recreate the value from flash without the client knowing so we would be able free some memory but still keep the interface the same.
Modified as suggested. Don't release key reference, reload key value from storage when needed.
Need to check for error.
Done

Possible future improvements:

 - Maybe instead of a hard limit on the number of items we try allocating memory first.  When that fails we start freeing items.  Otherwise, there is a possibility that memory would run out before we ever hit the number of items limit.

 - The two lists are treated separately but it might be more efficient to treat them together.  In fact, the digests are more likely to not be needed after first use so we could start freeing them first.  Ie. when memory allocation fails just start freeing digests then keys no matter what type of item is being created.

Yes, this can be saved in future.
1. Currently just use a hard number items limit. In future we could try allocate item first, if failed, free the item, then try to allocate the item again. This will complicate the logic. This function will only allocate item structure and I think item value (for asymmetric keys) will take a lot of memory and the malloc failure will likely happened there. The other ways to detect malloc failure might be to tapping into malloc function.
2. digest, AES key and asymmetric keys are quite different in terms of memory requirement. See benchmark:
https://confluence.sierrawireless.com/display/CP/IoTKeystore+Integration+Guide#IoTKeystoreIntegrationGuide-MemoryRequirements
"Per key memory requirement" table.
An asymmetric key takes about 10 times memory than symmetric key or digest. We could add some smart logic in future knowing that freeing asymmetric key will be more effective.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-14 - Add support for key provisioning using ECC

 - Add ECIES packet encryption and decryption functions.
 - Change ECIES tag size handling to match all other algorithms.
 - Create AES GCM internal functions that do not require an external
   client accessible session.
 - Replace ECIES implementation of AES GCM with calls to the internal
   AES GCM functions.
 - Create internal encryption and decryption functions for ECIES and
   RSA that do not require an external client accesible key reference.
 - Add key size to provisioning key export format to make processing
   easier.
 - Add definition for ECIES provisioning key wrap format.
 - Make all memory allocation use the mem API to make memory
   mesurement reliable.
 - Increase max parameters supported in QTEE RPC call from 12 to 16.
 - Add ECC support in local key wrapping and new test case for
   ECIES packet encryption/decryption.

ECC provisioning keys now work but support for the external authenticated server is not
functional and will be addressed in a future ticket.  So for now the unit tests will be run
only with an RSA provisioning key.

Change-Id: Id9d2f2582f7bee62fc06934b1c9c59875cae14af
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-14 - Add support for key provisioning using ECC

retry for ever. Treat return value 0 as an error condition

or ERR) can be turned on or off.
- Add very basic malloc/free statistic (number of
malloc/free events) to detect memory leak.
- Other general code cleanup.

Related: IOTKEYSTORE-32
Change-Id: Iee5fec9398a85308ce4794a9dddafaa85d80917c
Signed-off-by: Brad Du <bdu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-8 - Add log level and malloc statistic

comments.message:
I used to have an implementation that counts and reduces the exact amount of memory used, so that we can easily track which memory free is not seen expectedly.

For swi_malloc
actual_buffer = malloc (asked_size + sizeof(uint32))
mem_count += asked_size
buffer = (actual_buffer + sizeof(uint32))
return (buffer)

For swi_free
actual_buffer = buffer - sizeof(uint32)
mem_count -= *(uint32*) actual_buffer
free (actual_buffer)

Not sure if it's worth to bring it here.
Yes current mem_Free has the limitation that the exact number of bytes to be freed are unknown from the pointer. We could bring in this change if more advanced statistics are needed in future.
Why not using mem_Zeroize?
Done

IOTKEYSTORE-29 - Use the HMAC of identifiers for storage item names

 - Remove character restrictions for identifiers (all printable characters are now accepted).
 - Add pa_rpk_DeriveKey() function to get keys derived from the Root Protection Key.
 - Use a derived key for both the HMAC name key and the storage encryption key.
 - Move storage encryption code from PA to core.

Change-Id: I30ab719373811dd0c1de674a6e1af501b45b3b63
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-29 - Use the HMAC of identifiers for storage item names

comments.message:
This could change storage format and as we talked before this and other format changes need to be done in this early stage.
Why not save the ID as the first field, to align with line 717 digest format?

The storage format needs to change regardless and we need a way to change the storage in the field anyways (there's already a ticket for that).  Putting the key type first makes the decoding a little easier as the key type changes how the key value is interpreted.
Ack
Is there any problem with returning false (0) if unsuccessful here but iks_result_t 0 is IKS_OK? Also line 1338
Good catch.  This was a copy and paste error.

They namekey is stored in clear text since the namekey itself is needed to store it securely, right?
In other platforms, we might want to use a KDF function to derive namekey from hardware key.
So why not manage the namekey similar to Root Protection Key. i.e. move this logic to pa_store.c since it can be platform dependent.

The name key is not stored in clear text as the storage function provides confidentiality and integrity (encrypts and macs with the Root Protection Key).  Only the name of the name key is in the clear but I don't think this is much of a concern.  If we were to do a KDF to derive the name key we would still need to provide a static salt value so I don't know if it would be an improvement.  I don't see why this logic would need to be PA dependent.
Ack

I am thinking more on the use case and my concern is mainly on reliability. The namekey is basically a master key and if the namekey is somehow lost or removed in storage, all the existing keys in storage will not be accessed anymore. If a new random namekey is re-generated silently in case of lost, things looks normal but all older stored keys will not be accessed anymore and also these pre-existing keys are treated non-exists so they can be re-generated and bypass the security.
So I think we should give the PA the option to use hardcoded key or KDF derived key so that storage of this name key key will not be a concern.

How about add new PA function and add a hook here:
if  not pa_get_name_key(NameKey, &keySize)
  use the code here

Linux PA can have this PA function blank and return false.
Sounds good to me. A new PA function pa_Kdf function need to be created which can be useful for this and other cases.
Awesome.  Thanks for the great feedback.  I will make these changes.
do we need a return code to indicate whether or not all the bytes were converted (i.e. was there enough space)?

My intention was to allow the caller to be able to convert only the number of bytes wanted by specifying the output buffer size.  

But your question made me realize that if the output buffer is too large then the output buffer would contain unconverted bytes without the caller knowing.  I think instead of adding a return code I'll make the output buffer size an input/output parameter to indicate the actual number of converted bytes in the output.  What do you think?

Also, this function should be static.

If the output is supposed to be a NULL terminated string then the output buffer size might not be that useful?
Return code might be easier for caller to use.
OK, sounds good.

Some PA might not be able to handle a 3KB local var. Might need a malloc here. Current PAs can handle this. I see there are also some other large local vars, they can be reviewed and addressed in future.
Some PA might not be able to handle a 3KB local var. Might need a malloc here.

commits.commitMessage:
IOTKEYSTORE-21 - Perform local key wrapping

- Locally wrap known key values with the provisioning key to make testing with known
symmetric keys easier.

Change-Id: I256f888b5491011b1b0ebecffdd5e2980387bfd1
commits.subject: IOTKEYSTORE-21 - Perform local key wrapping

comments.message: why static? What happens if this function is called multiple times with different keyValSize parameter value?

The static makes the wrappingKey reference persistent across calls so it doesn't have to be fetched the next time.  Fetching it would work too, I don't have a preference.  Setting the wrapping key value each time could be avoided but that would make this function non-reentrant.

Calling this multiple times with different keyValSize parameters should be fine as the wrapping key could be used on different key sizes within its limit.

do we need to double check keyType decoded?
Will the following logic also work for ECC provision key?
No, the parameter decoding will not work for ECC provisioning keys.  So, yes a key type check would be good.  I will add that.
if the wrappingKey reference is static and valid, the key value will be valid too, right? Why do we need to set the value every time?

Since the creation of the key and the setting of the value is done in separate steps assuming the key value is valid when the key reference is valid would make this function non-reentrant.  Maybe a function like iks_HasKeyValue() should be added.  What do you think?
In that case, maybe using static wrappingKey reference didn't gain much so might just remove the static.
What do you think about the iks_HasKeyValue() function.  I think it'll provide more flexibility.
Yes, I think the new API iks_HasKeyValue() will be useful for this and other cases.
OK, I will add.  Thanks.
remove

  - Jira tickets:
        PROJECT-1234 - My summary
        PROJECT-1234 - [AR758x][Keyword] My summary
        PROJ1-1234 PROJ2-4567 - My summary with multiple tickets
 - Your commit should mention at least one ticket.
 - The second line of your commit message should be empty (currently '	IOTKEYSTORE-21 - Perform local key wrapping
It will be good if keyType can be printed out here to help with debug.
Done
